WEBVTT

00:00.540 --> 00:04.500
Meredith:
When I was in second grade,

00:04.500 --> 00:06.000
this girl, Missy,

00:06.000 --> 00:08.790
could cross her legs behind
her head like a pretzel.

00:08.790 --> 00:11.420
And one day,
her leg just popped,

00:11.420 --> 00:15.750
and then it was lying there,
behind her.

00:15.750 --> 00:18.000
My mother said, "Stop crying.

00:18.000 --> 00:19.920
It was just an anterior hip
dislocation."

00:19.920 --> 00:22.670
♪♪

00:22.670 --> 00:25.290
Then she said something
I've never forgotten.

00:25.290 --> 00:28.170
♪♪

00:28.170 --> 00:30.380
Mm...Nope.

00:30.380 --> 00:32.710
♪ Save it for
the sake of the fight ♪

00:32.710 --> 00:34.210
"Just because
you can do something..."

00:34.210 --> 00:35.540
[ Sighs ]

00:35.540 --> 00:37.080
"...doesn't mean you should."
[ Door opens ]

00:37.080 --> 00:42.250
♪ Copy/paste the child inside ♪

00:42.250 --> 00:45.540
♪ You used to smile,
but now you are staged ♪

00:45.540 --> 00:47.580
[ Elevator bell dings ]

00:47.580 --> 00:49.460
Hey.
♪ I hate to watch
you walk away ♪

00:49.460 --> 00:50.750
Hey.

00:50.750 --> 00:53.170
Did you spend the night here
again last night?

00:53.170 --> 00:56.040
Yeah. One of the lambs
had a rough night.
♪ I hate to watch
you walk away ♪

00:56.040 --> 00:57.420
I-I really need
some of that.

00:57.420 --> 00:59.540
It's actually for you.
It's a peace offering.

00:59.540 --> 01:01.750
♪♪

01:01.750 --> 01:03.290
I guess I was wrong
about your dad,

01:03.290 --> 01:05.920
and...it's none
of my business.

01:05.920 --> 01:07.460
No, it's --
it's not that --
I'm just --

01:07.460 --> 01:08.830
[ Elevator bell dings ]
I'm glad it's going well.

01:08.830 --> 01:10.040
I appreciate that.

01:10.040 --> 01:11.080
Yeah.

01:11.080 --> 01:13.420
And I really
appreciate this.

01:13.420 --> 01:16.830
♪♪

01:16.830 --> 01:18.330
Do you have a minute?

01:18.330 --> 01:22.290
♪ Save it for the sake
of our love ♪

01:22.290 --> 01:23.880
I missed you.

01:23.880 --> 01:26.000
♪ Raise a hand to show
that you're strong ♪

01:26.000 --> 01:28.120
You're not mad at me?

01:28.960 --> 01:30.290
♪ You used to smile,
but now you are shunned ♪

01:30.290 --> 01:33.920
So, if I was to stay at my place
one night this week,

01:33.920 --> 01:35.290
would you care to join me?

01:35.290 --> 01:37.080
♪ I hate
to watch you walk alone ♪

01:37.080 --> 01:40.170
That's the best idea
I've ever heard.

01:40.170 --> 01:41.960
I'll try to figure it out.

01:41.960 --> 01:46.580
♪ Is this how
you're gonna grow old? ♪

01:46.580 --> 01:48.080
I really should
get to work.

01:48.080 --> 01:51.420
♪ Is this how
you're gonna grow old? ♪

01:51.420 --> 01:53.540
And you should get
some sleep, Doctor.

01:53.540 --> 01:55.830
♪ Is this how
you're gonna grow old? ♪
[ Chuckles ]

01:55.830 --> 01:57.290
Don't forget your coffee.

01:57.290 --> 01:58.830
-I'm already wide awake.
-[ Chuckles ]

01:58.830 --> 02:00.830
[ Door opens, closes ]

02:00.830 --> 02:03.040
Jackson:
Keep your cuts straight.

02:03.040 --> 02:04.880
You want to go
into the dermis.

02:04.880 --> 02:07.830
Stay as shallow as we can.

02:07.830 --> 02:09.460
Wonder if the guys
at Pike Street Market

02:09.460 --> 02:11.750
went to four years
of medical school.

02:11.750 --> 02:12.670
[ Door opens, closes ]

02:12.670 --> 02:14.420
Hey. So...

02:14.420 --> 02:16.670
I think I should cancel
this thing tomorrow.

02:17.710 --> 02:19.080
Oh, my God.

02:19.080 --> 02:20.500
Honestly, I don't even
smell it anymore.

02:20.500 --> 02:22.380
I do.

02:22.380 --> 02:24.290
Yeah, I-I'm not going on
"Good Morning Seattle."

02:24.290 --> 02:27.460
A podcast was one thing,
but television?

02:27.460 --> 02:29.710
Plus, it's not even
about medicine anymore.

02:29.710 --> 02:32.290
It's -- It's
"Genius surgeon finds out

02:32.290 --> 02:33.620
she's the illegitimate
love-child

02:33.620 --> 02:34.790
of other genius surgeons."

02:34.790 --> 02:36.380
I'm morning show fodder.

02:36.380 --> 02:39.210
You're in the genius surgeon
segment, okay?

02:39.210 --> 02:42.000
It's not like you're going in
there to make French toast.

02:42.000 --> 02:43.460
No, that would be the worst
segment in the world.

02:43.460 --> 02:44.830
They'd just be watching me
fishing around

02:44.830 --> 02:46.250
looking for eggshells
with my fingers.

02:46.250 --> 02:47.790
Yet I would still
pay to see that.

02:47.790 --> 02:49.170
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

02:49.170 --> 02:50.380
So you're saying
I shouldn't cancel it?

02:50.380 --> 02:51.750
I'm saying
it shoots tomorrow,

02:51.750 --> 02:52.960
and it's too late
to cancel.

02:52.960 --> 02:54.170
Don't be nervous.

02:54.170 --> 02:55.580
You're gonna do great.

02:55.580 --> 02:57.170
Okay.
[ Chuckling ] Okay?

02:57.170 --> 03:00.250
Why are your interns
making sushi?

03:00.250 --> 03:01.830
Well...
Oh, is this your thing?

03:01.830 --> 03:02.920
Well, I have to
get out of here.

03:02.920 --> 03:05.040
I can't go on TV
smelling like fish.

03:05.040 --> 03:08.290
♪♪

03:08.290 --> 03:10.710
Why can't we practice
on cadavers?

03:10.710 --> 03:12.380
Formaldehyde smells nicer.

03:12.380 --> 03:13.710
This is not for
your scalpel technique.

03:13.710 --> 03:15.170
It's not?

03:15.170 --> 03:16.080
Then why?

03:17.620 --> 03:19.380
This is why.

03:19.380 --> 03:21.540
♪♪

03:21.540 --> 03:23.620
Oh, that's...

03:23.620 --> 03:25.380
-Ohh.
-Fantastic.

03:25.380 --> 03:26.750
Hey, Rick.

03:26.750 --> 03:29.460
[ Indistinct whispering ]

03:29.460 --> 03:31.540
We're making
fish people.

03:31.540 --> 03:32.540
[ Gasps ]

03:40.170 --> 03:41.920
It is very disturbing.

03:41.920 --> 03:43.500
Have y-you seen it?

03:43.500 --> 03:46.170
The little laminated lambs
kicking in their little bags.

03:46.170 --> 03:47.420
It's pretty amazing, huh?

03:47.420 --> 03:50.250
When I look at the fetal lamb
in a bag,

03:50.250 --> 03:53.250
I imagine the next step would
be a fetal human in a bag.

03:53.250 --> 03:54.750
And if anything
goes wrong with that,

03:54.750 --> 03:56.750
we are in an ethical
and legal quagmire

03:56.750 --> 04:00.670
that you created and will have
left me holding the...quag.

04:00.670 --> 04:02.830
That's funny, but I imagine
rewriting the paradigm

04:02.830 --> 04:05.620
of at-risk pregnancies,
saving premature babies.
Ohh.

04:05.620 --> 04:07.710
And he's a long way
from human trials.

04:07.710 --> 04:10.750
And are you sure it's good
to go down this road?

04:10.750 --> 04:13.210
I mean, I'm hearing things
about this Dr. DeLuca

04:13.210 --> 04:15.250
having a history
of mental illness...

04:15.250 --> 04:16.830
We should discriminate
against people for that?

04:16.830 --> 04:17.960
[ Scoffs ] Of course not.

04:17.960 --> 04:19.380
But we should ask questions

04:19.380 --> 04:21.080
when they start putting babies
in bags.

04:21.080 --> 04:22.960
Bailey, my mom came out
here by herself.

04:22.960 --> 04:24.460
She's been in my apartment
for over a week --

04:24.460 --> 04:27.380
no routine, no being chained
to a library desk.

04:27.380 --> 04:29.830
And even if Dr. DeLuca does
suffer from mental illness,

04:29.830 --> 04:31.330
we need to support people --

04:31.330 --> 04:32.540
Hellmouth, what?

04:32.540 --> 04:35.120
Hi, hello.
Sorry. Uh, hi.

04:35.120 --> 04:36.670
I, uh, was wondering
if you might

04:36.670 --> 04:40.250
want to take a stroll
by Dr. DeLuca Sr.'s lab --

04:40.250 --> 04:41.790
or, more specifically,
you should --

04:41.790 --> 04:43.000
you should do that.

04:44.620 --> 04:48.830
[ Speaking Italian ]

04:48.830 --> 04:51.330
[ Speaking Italian ]

04:51.330 --> 04:53.960
[ Speaking Italian ]

04:53.960 --> 04:56.380
Excuse me.

04:56.380 --> 04:57.920
Did you call
the headmaster now?

04:57.920 --> 04:59.290
What's the problem?

04:59.290 --> 05:00.580
He lost a lamb.

05:00.580 --> 05:03.170
One subject expired.

05:03.170 --> 05:04.790
A minor setback,
to be expected.

05:04.790 --> 05:06.170
We think that it --

05:06.170 --> 05:08.120
Babies die in womb
all the time.

05:08.120 --> 05:09.790
Papa,
you're working very fast.

05:09.790 --> 05:11.500
Y-You are too impatient.
Hey!

05:11.500 --> 05:13.750
You don't like the way I work,
you can get out.

05:13.750 --> 05:16.000
I'm not saying that I --
Go!

05:16.000 --> 05:18.670
I will miss your bold vision.

05:18.670 --> 05:21.580
You, who chose a career
helping women have babies --

05:21.580 --> 05:24.250
a thing she can do by herself
since the dawn of time.

05:24.250 --> 05:25.830
Go.

05:25.830 --> 05:27.500
[ Keyboard clacking ]

05:27.500 --> 05:29.710
♪♪

05:29.710 --> 05:31.040
Capo.

05:31.040 --> 05:32.710
Something needed?

05:32.710 --> 05:36.920
♪♪

05:36.920 --> 05:38.080
[ Whispers ] Quagmire.

05:39.830 --> 05:41.290
[ Sighs ]

05:41.290 --> 05:42.330
[ Horn honks ]
[ Indistinct conversations ]

05:42.330 --> 05:43.920
-Hey.
-Where have you been?

05:43.920 --> 05:45.670
I paged you like
15 minutes ago.

05:45.670 --> 05:47.830
I think you meant to say,
"Thank you for covering me

05:47.830 --> 05:49.460
when me and my boyfriend
went away for four days."

05:49.460 --> 05:51.790
I meant to say
you're late.
[ Siren wailing ]

05:51.790 --> 05:54.500
[ Sighs ] I ran into trouble
with Leo this morning,

05:54.500 --> 05:56.960
and Amelia's
at a conference.

05:56.960 --> 05:59.290
Actually, Amelia's...

05:59.290 --> 06:01.540
out of the picture,
which is...

06:01.540 --> 06:03.750
You know, Amelia, she would
sometimes help with Leo,

06:03.750 --> 06:05.460
but this morning,
it was all me.

06:05.460 --> 06:06.920
Not that it matters,
you know?

06:06.920 --> 06:08.920
I can handle Leo on my own.
I do just fine.

06:08.920 --> 06:10.000
I didn't say anything.
[ Ambulance doors open ]

06:10.000 --> 06:11.290
Hey.

06:11.290 --> 06:13.380
MVC rollover,
male in his 20s,

06:13.380 --> 06:15.960
possible fractured clavicle --
stable vitals.

06:15.960 --> 06:17.540
His wife's next door.
You should see her first.

06:17.540 --> 06:19.330
I'll see you
in Trauma 2.
Paramedic: Lizzie Hall, 22,

06:19.330 --> 06:20.750
oriented to person
on the scene,

06:20.750 --> 06:23.330
pressure's in the 90s,
GCS 13 in the field.

06:23.330 --> 06:25.120
Teddy: All right.
Trauma 1, let's go.

06:25.120 --> 06:26.920
Leo and I are great,
just me and him.

06:26.920 --> 06:28.960
I'm great with him, okay?
I didn't say anything.

06:28.960 --> 06:31.960
Suddenly, I feel like
I'm auditioning to be a father.

06:31.960 --> 06:34.920
[ Indistinct conversations ]

06:34.920 --> 06:43.420
♪♪

06:43.420 --> 06:45.420
Excuse me.
Is this the, uh, line?

06:45.420 --> 06:47.250
Hey.
Hey!

06:47.250 --> 06:48.830
[ Chuckles ]
What are you doing here?

06:48.830 --> 06:50.920
Uh...

06:50.920 --> 06:52.960
Well,
like the banners say,

06:52.960 --> 06:56.290
Western States Conference
for Alternative Pain Relief.

06:56.290 --> 06:58.210
Right. I didn't, uh -- didn't
know you were into this stuff.

06:58.210 --> 06:59.580
Yeah, I'm not.

06:59.580 --> 07:01.960
I mean, I'm interested,

07:01.960 --> 07:05.420
ever since that day
with the mass overdose.

07:05.420 --> 07:06.670
Yeah. Tough day.

07:06.670 --> 07:08.620
Yes.

07:08.620 --> 07:12.170
I cried at you,
convulsively.

07:12.170 --> 07:13.670
You might recall.

07:13.670 --> 07:16.000
I haven't seen you around
much since then.

07:16.000 --> 07:17.250
Yeah, that was intentional.

07:17.250 --> 07:19.620
It's hard to know where
to go after that.

07:19.620 --> 07:23.120
Anyway, I'm, uh, newly into it.
How about you?

07:23.120 --> 07:24.920
Uh, I do, like,
three of these a year, yeah.

07:24.920 --> 07:26.710
I'm giving a lecture.

07:26.710 --> 07:28.380
Wow.

07:28.380 --> 07:30.380
W-When is that?
Tomorrow.

07:30.380 --> 07:34.460
Uh, but right now, I was gonna
hit up this acupuncture demo.

07:34.460 --> 07:36.290
Interested?

07:36.290 --> 07:39.540
Uh, well, I'm headed to this
next-generation NSAIDs panel.

07:39.540 --> 07:42.330
But...no, you know what?
I think I'd rather get poked.

07:43.580 --> 07:46.580
With needles.

07:46.580 --> 07:48.500
Never mind.

07:48.500 --> 07:50.080
I'm gonna keep avoiding you.

07:51.620 --> 07:52.540
Have a nice time.

07:52.540 --> 07:55.290
♪♪

07:55.290 --> 07:56.330
[ Chuckling ] Okay.

07:56.330 --> 07:57.460
[ Whispering ]
Oh, my God.

07:57.460 --> 07:59.040
♪♪

08:04.540 --> 08:07.040
Levi: Sir, do you have any pain
when I do this?
No, I don't.

08:07.040 --> 08:08.170
Great.
C-spine's cleared.

08:08.170 --> 08:10.460
[ Breathes sharply ]

08:10.460 --> 08:12.460
You paged?
Left clavicular fracture

08:12.460 --> 08:14.420
and a possible fracture
of the distal humerus.

08:14.420 --> 08:15.830
Hey, is my wife okay?

08:15.830 --> 08:16.880
She is right next door.
She's being --

08:16.880 --> 08:18.170
What about my baby?

08:18.170 --> 08:19.790
She's --
Is my baby all right?

08:21.460 --> 08:23.250
They didn't bring a baby in.

08:23.250 --> 08:24.880
Was there a baby
in the car?
No, no, my, um --

08:24.880 --> 08:27.710
My wife, um, she's --
she's -- ow.

08:27.710 --> 08:29.580
She's five months pregnant.

08:29.580 --> 08:30.880
Oh.

08:30.880 --> 08:33.250
Um, Schmitt, you can start
on these abrasions.

08:33.250 --> 08:35.750
Um, I'm gonna be right back,
okay?

08:35.750 --> 08:37.210
Okay.

08:37.210 --> 08:38.540
I'm doing a central line.

08:38.540 --> 08:39.670
Lidocaine.

08:41.170 --> 08:43.000
Hey.
Switch with me.

08:43.000 --> 08:45.620
What? I'm just
about to do --
She's pregnant.

08:45.620 --> 08:47.290
Five months.

08:47.290 --> 08:49.580
Switch with me,
and you can take the husband.

08:49.580 --> 08:50.830
I'm fine.

08:50.830 --> 08:53.000
Page OB. She's pregnant.

08:53.000 --> 08:55.000
[ Sighs ] And get
an ultrasound, please.

08:55.000 --> 08:56.500
[ Monitor beeping ]

08:56.500 --> 08:58.040
Okay.

09:01.210 --> 09:02.580
Figure out
why the lamb died,

09:02.580 --> 09:04.040
write a report,
and I'll review it.

09:04.040 --> 09:05.250
Look, I'll talk to Papa
about getting you back

09:05.250 --> 09:06.670
on the research project,
all right?

09:06.670 --> 09:08.670
I don't want back
on this project.

09:08.670 --> 09:11.000
Andrea, stop pretending
you don't see it.

09:11.000 --> 09:14.250
These swings -- he's up, he's
down, he's funny, he's cruel.

09:14.250 --> 09:15.620
[ Cellphone buzzing ]
He is bipolar.

09:15.620 --> 09:18.580
He refuses to acknowledge it,
and now you are, too.

09:18.580 --> 09:20.120
I'm being paged
to The Hole.

09:20.120 --> 09:22.540
The Pit. Go.

09:22.540 --> 09:25.460
This is an important project,
but my father --

09:25.460 --> 09:27.120
Is the one who
brought it here.

09:27.120 --> 09:29.580
Could ruin it
if you let him.

09:30.960 --> 09:32.750
Is that your take?

09:32.750 --> 09:34.750
Look, he's not easy.
H-He's never been easy.

09:34.750 --> 09:36.250
But neither is my sister,
and she doesn't have

09:36.250 --> 09:37.960
the right degree
to diagnose him.

09:37.960 --> 09:39.790
The two of them, they --
they do this.

09:39.790 --> 09:41.040
Always have.

09:41.040 --> 09:42.620
Get me that report.

09:42.620 --> 09:44.670
Woman on P.A.:
Neuro resident to the ER.

09:47.750 --> 09:49.460
Maggie, you're adopted.

09:49.460 --> 09:51.330
Yeah, I'd heard that.
And good morning.

09:51.330 --> 09:52.540
I know. Sorry, um...

09:52.540 --> 09:54.000
I was just wondering,
did you ever

09:54.000 --> 09:55.620
get your DNA tested?

09:55.620 --> 09:56.620
Have you met me?

09:56.620 --> 09:58.120
I battered myself
with tests.

09:58.120 --> 10:00.120
I-I wanted to know
everything.

10:00.120 --> 10:01.960
My DNA results.

10:01.960 --> 10:02.920
I don't want
to open them alone,

10:02.920 --> 10:04.000
but I don't want
to open them with Alex

10:04.000 --> 10:05.670
and have to watch his face

10:05.670 --> 10:07.710
if he discovers that his wife
is a genetic lemon.

10:07.710 --> 10:10.380
I'm your girl.
Look, I know this can be scary.

10:10.380 --> 10:11.830
But I promise,
whatever we find...

10:11.830 --> 10:13.880
Ugh, what stinks in here?

10:13.880 --> 10:16.080
That's me, sorry.
I washed my hands, but...

10:16.080 --> 10:17.170
[ Clears throat ]

10:17.170 --> 10:18.670
All right, you ready?

10:18.670 --> 10:20.120
Mm-hmm.

10:20.120 --> 10:21.920
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

10:21.920 --> 10:22.880
[ Exhales sharply ]

10:22.880 --> 10:25.080
Alzheimer's, no.

10:25.080 --> 10:26.380
Okay.

10:26.380 --> 10:27.710
Huntington's, no.

10:27.710 --> 10:30.170
Parkinson's, no.

10:30.170 --> 10:32.540
Congratulations.
You won the genetic lottery.

10:32.540 --> 10:34.620
[ Chuckles ]

10:34.620 --> 10:36.790
It says here
I'm mostly British.

10:36.790 --> 10:38.080
Congrats.

10:38.080 --> 10:39.290
I got a patient.

10:39.290 --> 10:41.040
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Sussman to Peds ICU.

10:41.040 --> 10:41.960
Dr. Sussman to Peds ICU.

10:41.960 --> 10:43.830
Oh, my...

10:43.830 --> 10:47.960
"You are comparing
with Martha Tomlinson.

10:47.960 --> 10:49.830
It's probable that
Martha Tomlinson

10:49.830 --> 10:51.830
is your first cousin."

10:54.710 --> 10:56.250
I have a cousin.

10:58.330 --> 10:59.540
[ Scoffs ]
Do you want me
to find her?

11:00.880 --> 11:02.170
How would you do that?

11:02.170 --> 11:04.120
Start with a Web search,
then Facebook, Instagram,

11:04.120 --> 11:05.380
then an exhaustive search

11:05.380 --> 11:06.880
of various consumer
databases --

11:06.880 --> 11:08.460
No, no, no, no!
I don't want that!

11:08.460 --> 11:09.920
No, that's --
that's creepy.

11:09.920 --> 11:11.290
It's all legal.

11:11.290 --> 11:12.460
No.

11:15.750 --> 11:17.420
Okay, but
if you could find her,

11:17.420 --> 11:19.920
could you also find out
who she's related to?

11:19.920 --> 11:22.290
Could you find
her mother or --

11:22.290 --> 11:24.580
Or your mother?
No!

11:24.580 --> 11:25.830
I didn't say do it.

11:36.330 --> 11:38.290
Oh. [ Chuckles ]

11:38.290 --> 11:39.540
Okay.

11:39.540 --> 11:40.540
Hello again.

11:42.880 --> 11:44.250
You want me to move?

11:44.250 --> 11:46.790
No, of course not.
Man: Shhh!

11:46.790 --> 11:48.210
[ Sighing ] Oh, God.

11:50.380 --> 11:53.880
[ Breathes deeply ]

11:53.880 --> 11:55.420
What does this do?

11:55.420 --> 11:58.250
The frequencies respond

11:58.250 --> 12:00.210
to the energy meridians
and, uh, resonate --

12:00.210 --> 12:02.210
"Energy meridians."

12:02.210 --> 12:03.540
Oh, my God.

12:03.540 --> 12:06.210
Woman: Shh!

12:06.210 --> 12:07.830
You're not
supposed to talk.

12:07.830 --> 12:09.710
Yeah, I'm not supposed
to be here.

12:09.710 --> 12:12.830
[ Gong ringing ]

12:17.540 --> 12:19.750
[ Exhales slowly ]

12:19.750 --> 12:21.330
[ Breathes deeply ]

12:21.330 --> 12:24.540
[ Ringing continues ]

12:24.540 --> 12:29.830
♪♪

12:29.830 --> 12:30.920
Teddy:
Free fluid in her abdomen.

12:30.920 --> 12:33.380
Fetal heartbeat is good.

12:33.380 --> 12:34.960
Baby?

12:34.960 --> 12:36.460
Hey, Lizzie.

12:36.460 --> 12:37.580
You with us?

12:37.580 --> 12:38.750
I'm Dr. Altman.

12:38.750 --> 12:40.290
You're bleeding
from your abdomen,

12:40.290 --> 12:41.790
and I need to find
where it's coming from.

12:41.790 --> 12:43.040
My baby's okay?

12:43.040 --> 12:44.620
Your baby's great,
Lizzie.

12:44.620 --> 12:47.250
Strong heartbeat, moving,
no signs of distress.

12:47.250 --> 12:49.790
Yes, but --
It was a surprise.

12:49.790 --> 12:51.920
We were gonna wait,
like, five years.

12:51.920 --> 12:54.580
We just got married,
but when we found out,

12:54.580 --> 12:57.330
we were just like, "Yay!"

12:57.330 --> 12:58.830
All right, Lizzie.
You sit tight.

12:58.830 --> 13:00.920
Can I talk to you outside
for a minute, please?
Yeah.

13:02.120 --> 13:04.710
[ Beeping continues ]

13:04.710 --> 13:06.620
I know you're seeing
a healthy baby,

13:06.620 --> 13:08.460
but I'm seeing a mother
with a belly full of blood,

13:08.460 --> 13:10.580
and to save her, I might
have to remove her uterus

13:10.580 --> 13:11.830
along with the baby.

13:11.830 --> 13:14.620
The baby's no more
than 21 weeks.

13:14.620 --> 13:15.920
It cannot survive
outside --
I know.

13:15.920 --> 13:17.620
And I have to tell her now,

13:17.620 --> 13:19.460
and you just made it so much
harder for her to hear.

13:19.460 --> 13:21.500
So please keep your mouth shut
and check with me

13:21.500 --> 13:24.500
if you need to talk to her
again, all right?

13:24.500 --> 13:25.880
I-I-I'm sorry.

13:25.880 --> 13:26.920
[ Sighs ]

13:32.710 --> 13:35.120
Jackson: Brazil's been using
tilapia skin to treat burns

13:35.120 --> 13:36.500
for years now --
decrease the scarring,

13:36.500 --> 13:38.710
costs nothing compared
to standard treatments,

13:38.710 --> 13:41.710
and it just peels away.

13:41.710 --> 13:42.710
Incredible.

13:42.710 --> 13:44.250
My interns stink.

13:44.250 --> 13:46.170
Yeah, and with its restorative
properties --

13:46.170 --> 13:47.920
It smells like high tide.

13:47.920 --> 13:49.380
Patients are complaining,

13:49.380 --> 13:52.750
and I do not enjoy breathing
through my mouth.

13:52.750 --> 13:59.420
♪♪

13:59.420 --> 14:01.290
Explain.

14:01.290 --> 14:03.420
It's part of my spray-on
skin research.

14:03.420 --> 14:05.170
He made us skin the fish.

14:06.540 --> 14:08.670
Well, what do you do with
the other parts of the fish?

14:08.670 --> 14:10.830
Oh, that's medical waste.

14:10.830 --> 14:13.380
Well, that's a crime.

14:13.380 --> 14:15.290
What -- What is it? Uh.

14:15.290 --> 14:18.000
Oh, that looks like
tilapia.

14:18.000 --> 14:20.040
Yeah, that's good fish.

14:20.040 --> 14:22.420
Lambs in a bag,
fish skin on people.

14:22.420 --> 14:23.960
I mean, what's next here?

14:23.960 --> 14:26.500
Next is the machines come to
life and take over the world.

14:26.500 --> 14:30.620
♪♪

14:30.620 --> 14:31.830
Never mind.

14:31.830 --> 14:34.460
[ Tray clatters ]

14:34.460 --> 14:36.080
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Gennis to the ER.

14:36.080 --> 14:37.670
Dr. Ed Gennis to the ER.

14:37.670 --> 14:39.540
Mrs. Karev?

14:39.540 --> 14:40.750
Hello.

14:40.750 --> 14:43.040
D-- Uh, I'm, uh,
Dr. Miranda Bailey.

14:43.040 --> 14:45.670
I was Alex's chief resident
when he first came here.

14:45.670 --> 14:48.790
Oh, my gosh. Hi. It's so --
I'm happy to meet you.

14:48.790 --> 14:50.580
[ Laughs ]
Here. Sit, please.

14:50.580 --> 14:51.920
Oh, thank you.

14:51.920 --> 14:53.170
[ Chuckles ]

14:55.210 --> 14:57.290
Wow. You must be proud,

14:57.290 --> 14:59.960
Alex making it all the way
to chief of the hospital.

14:59.960 --> 15:01.710
[ Chuckles ]
Mmmmmm.

15:01.710 --> 15:04.000
So, what are you
knitting here?

15:04.000 --> 15:07.420
Well, it was a scarf
that became a sweater,

15:07.420 --> 15:11.040
and then I just kind of
kept going, and now it's...

15:11.040 --> 15:11.960
Oh.
Now it's --

15:11.960 --> 15:14.750
It's maybe a car cover.

15:14.750 --> 15:17.170
[ Laughs ]

15:17.170 --> 15:19.040
Alex said you'd
extended your stay,

15:19.040 --> 15:20.710
so you must be having
a good time.

15:20.710 --> 15:22.750
I don't travel much.

15:22.750 --> 15:26.880
And, uh, I'm glad I did it,
but it's been a lot for me.

15:28.580 --> 15:30.920
I'm a little nervous about
making the trip back.

15:30.920 --> 15:34.500
Oh, I see. Um, have you
told Alex or...?
No.

15:34.500 --> 15:37.580
No, they've both been so great,
Jo and Alex.

15:37.580 --> 15:40.420
I-I... [ Sighs ]
They're just so busy.

15:40.420 --> 15:42.880
I'll feel better. I will.

15:42.880 --> 15:44.710
I'm just so ready
to be home.

15:49.830 --> 15:52.330
[ Breathes deeply ]

15:52.330 --> 15:54.210
Hey. How is she?

15:54.210 --> 15:56.330
Hey. Um...

15:56.330 --> 15:58.120
Stable, for now.

15:58.120 --> 15:59.460
Uh, so, before
the husband wakes up,

15:59.460 --> 16:00.500
I just wanted to
get the update.

16:00.500 --> 16:01.880
Their baby is...?

16:01.880 --> 16:03.170
Right where they left it.

16:03.170 --> 16:04.460
What?

16:04.460 --> 16:06.210
Yeah. The CT showed
that the bleed

16:06.210 --> 16:09.960
was coming from the right
uterine artery, so I embolized.

16:09.960 --> 16:12.580
And the baby's blood supply
is coming from the left side.

16:12.580 --> 16:13.830
She seems happy with it.

16:13.830 --> 16:15.290
[ Scoffs ]

16:15.290 --> 16:17.710
Teddy, you saved
their baby.

16:17.710 --> 16:19.580
Well, we'll see.

16:19.580 --> 16:22.250
I mean, I hope she
doesn't re-bleed.
Mm.

16:22.250 --> 16:24.580
-How's the husband?
-Oh, he --

16:24.580 --> 16:27.420
Fractured clavicle,
a small humerus fracture.
[ Groans ]

16:27.420 --> 16:28.330
He's gonna be fine.

16:30.250 --> 16:31.460
Go home. Get sleep.

16:31.460 --> 16:32.880
No, I'm gonna stay
in case.

16:32.880 --> 16:34.960
I-I want to make sure
all three leave together.

16:34.960 --> 16:37.080
I'll do that.
I'll stay.

16:37.080 --> 16:39.080
No.

16:39.080 --> 16:41.790
You need to get sleep,
and the baby needs sleep.

16:41.790 --> 16:45.710
So, go and -- I don't know --
have Koracick rub your feet.

16:45.710 --> 16:47.080
[ Laughing ] Owen...

16:47.080 --> 16:49.080
She's my patient.

16:49.080 --> 16:51.960
And Tom is at Hopkins
for the week.

16:51.960 --> 16:53.380
[ Monitor beeping ]

16:53.380 --> 16:55.040
I'll be fine.
I'm just -- I'm gonna --

16:55.040 --> 16:56.830
I'm gonna sleep
right here.

16:56.830 --> 16:59.080
[ Sighs ]
Hey.

16:59.080 --> 17:00.540
Go.

17:00.540 --> 17:02.920
[ Sighs ]

17:02.920 --> 17:04.880
[ Breathes sharply ]

17:04.880 --> 17:06.830
[ Breathes deeply ]

17:06.830 --> 17:08.420
Okay.

17:08.420 --> 17:12.250
[ Beeping continues ]

17:12.250 --> 17:15.380
Well, I mean,
if you're gonna sit there...

17:15.380 --> 17:16.120
Hm?

17:17.790 --> 17:19.250
You could rub my feet.

17:19.250 --> 17:20.920
♪♪

17:20.920 --> 17:24.210
Really?
[ Laughing ]
You brought it up.

17:24.210 --> 17:26.080
♪ White frost
on the horizon ♪
Okay.

17:26.080 --> 17:30.170
♪ I lost nearly my mind ♪

17:30.170 --> 17:31.380
♪♪

17:31.380 --> 17:33.710
[ Breathes deeply ]

17:33.710 --> 17:36.460
♪ Having no one beside me
but pining ♪
Did that make you
feel dizzy, the sound?

17:36.460 --> 17:38.290
Like -- Like loopy?
♪ I bear the loss ♪

17:38.290 --> 17:39.960
No, it just kind of
chilled me out.

17:39.960 --> 17:41.960
I-I feel like
I need a meeting.

17:41.960 --> 17:44.120
Whew!
♪ Having let
Mother Nature define me ♪

17:44.120 --> 17:46.380
Hey, could we sit
for a sec, you think?

17:46.380 --> 17:47.460
Yeah. Yeah, yeah.
Let's just find someplace to --

17:47.460 --> 17:49.960
Okay.
♪ We paid the cost ♪

17:49.960 --> 17:52.670
[ Exhales sharply ]

17:52.670 --> 17:54.210
[ Clears throat ]

17:54.210 --> 17:55.580
♪ Isn't it a pity
what's lost... ♪

17:55.580 --> 17:57.330
Sorry. I'm falling
apart here.

17:57.330 --> 18:00.920
♪ ...in the meridian of time? ♪
You don't need to apologize.

18:00.920 --> 18:03.210
♪ It's your touch ♪
I had a foster kid.

18:03.210 --> 18:04.710
♪ It's your touch ♪

18:04.710 --> 18:06.040
Sort of.

18:06.040 --> 18:07.920
♪ It's you ♪
Betty...

18:09.920 --> 18:12.920
Um, she was an addict
and a runaway,

18:12.920 --> 18:14.210
and I took her in and...

18:14.210 --> 18:15.210
♪ White frost on the horizon ♪

18:15.210 --> 18:17.040
...tried to help her
get clean

18:17.040 --> 18:20.040
and tried
and tried and...
♪ I once covered our heart ♪

18:20.040 --> 18:23.170
And I tried
some more and...

18:23.170 --> 18:24.330
♪ Having
no even temper confided ♪

18:24.330 --> 18:27.920
And then her parents
came back,

18:27.920 --> 18:30.290
and she went back
with them.
♪ I bear the loss ♪

18:30.290 --> 18:32.750
♪♪

18:32.750 --> 18:34.170
♪ I'd been living
a nation divided ♪

18:34.170 --> 18:36.750
And I miss her.

18:36.750 --> 18:39.380
♪ Deeper the cost ♪
And I don't know
if she's okay.

18:39.380 --> 18:44.080
And I don't know
if she'll be okay.

18:44.080 --> 18:45.540
♪ Summon the committee ♪

18:45.540 --> 18:47.000
And I don't feel done.

18:47.000 --> 18:49.330
♪ We still vote
with an aye ♪

18:49.330 --> 18:51.330
You sound like...

18:51.330 --> 18:53.290
♪ It's your touch ♪
A mess? [ Sighs ]

18:53.290 --> 18:56.040
♪ It's your touch ♪
A parent.

18:56.040 --> 18:57.250
♪ It's you ♪

18:57.250 --> 18:59.460
My mom cried
for like three months

18:59.460 --> 19:01.920
after I went away to college,
and I wasn't a drug addict.

19:01.920 --> 19:02.920
♪ It's your touch ♪

19:02.920 --> 19:05.380
♪ It's your touch ♪

19:05.380 --> 19:06.790
Thank you.
♪ It's you ♪

19:06.790 --> 19:09.960
♪♪

19:09.960 --> 19:11.920
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

19:11.920 --> 19:14.210
My God.
♪ Ooh ♪

19:14.210 --> 19:16.040
You are just chiseled.
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

19:16.040 --> 19:18.710
[ Chuckles ]
Like a statue.

19:18.710 --> 19:21.290
It's like your chin
has muscles.
[ Laughs ]

19:21.290 --> 19:23.710
Yeah, well, I do work out
my chin pretty hard.

19:23.710 --> 19:25.330
It takes a whole day.
[ Laughs ]

19:25.330 --> 19:26.500
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

19:26.500 --> 19:28.580
♪♪

19:28.580 --> 19:32.750
♪ I've been living
a nation divided ♪

19:32.750 --> 19:35.170
♪ We bear the loss ♪

19:35.170 --> 19:37.920
I should go to my room.

19:37.920 --> 19:41.380
And I should go...
♪ Having let Mother Nature
define me ♪

19:41.380 --> 19:43.670
To your room.
...to my room.

19:43.670 --> 19:45.620
♪ Deeper the cost ♪

19:45.620 --> 19:47.920
You have a presentation
tomorrow,

19:47.920 --> 19:51.420
and I am not fit
for human contact.
♪ It's your touch ♪

19:51.420 --> 19:52.830
♪ It's your touch ♪

19:52.830 --> 19:53.920
♪ It's you ♪
See you in the morning?

19:53.920 --> 19:55.080
Yeah.

19:56.880 --> 19:57.960
Night.

19:57.960 --> 20:00.500
Night.

20:00.500 --> 20:02.210
Gonna...

20:02.210 --> 20:05.540
♪♪

20:05.540 --> 20:08.000
Owen: [ Distorted ]
Teddy. Teddy!

20:08.000 --> 20:09.620
[ Rushing air echoes ]

20:09.620 --> 20:11.380
[ Distorted conversation ]

20:11.380 --> 20:13.040
[ Monitor beeping rapidly
in distance ]

20:13.040 --> 20:15.210
[ Normal voice ]
Teddy. Teddy!

20:15.210 --> 20:17.080
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
What?

20:17.080 --> 20:18.540
What is it?
Her BP bottomed out.

20:18.540 --> 20:20.040
Nurse: Baby's monitor
is showing decels.

20:20.040 --> 20:21.120
Okay. I'm giving her
two units of blood,

20:21.120 --> 20:22.670
and her pressure
is coming back up.

20:22.670 --> 20:24.040
All right. Book an OR!

20:24.040 --> 20:26.000
Get ready for...

20:26.000 --> 20:27.330
If I can't stop
the bleeding,

20:27.330 --> 20:28.420
I'm gonna have to take
her uterus out.

20:28.420 --> 20:30.290
Yeah. Do you want
me to do it?
Owen, stop it --

20:30.290 --> 20:31.500
Teddy, I'm not saying
that you can't.

20:31.500 --> 20:33.080
I'm just saying
you don't have to.

20:33.080 --> 20:34.830
I know you feel you should be,
but you don't have to be there

20:34.830 --> 20:35.920
if this woman
loses her baby.

20:35.920 --> 20:37.580
Thank you. I'm okay.

20:37.580 --> 20:39.460
You could get
the father in here

20:39.460 --> 20:41.620
so we can tell them
what's going on.
Okay.

20:41.620 --> 20:43.380
[ Beeping continues ]

20:43.380 --> 20:46.710
Add, uh, 1 liter of lactated
Ringer's, please.

20:46.710 --> 20:47.880
Okay.

20:50.500 --> 20:53.420
Your sister
has turned on me.

20:53.420 --> 20:55.750
Papa, nobody's
turned on you, okay?

20:55.750 --> 20:57.830
But you need to learn
how to control your temper.

20:57.830 --> 20:58.960
People are getting
concerned about you,

20:58.960 --> 21:00.460
and I'm trying to
back you up here.

21:00.460 --> 21:02.830
But I can't if you
keep throwing tantrums.

21:02.830 --> 21:05.620
Okay. I'll call her here.
We'll talk like a family.

21:05.620 --> 21:07.250
No, no, no. Papa, no.
Not now.

21:07.250 --> 21:09.170
I just spoke to her.
She needs some time.

21:09.170 --> 21:11.120
Plus, she's got
this pregnant trauma patient

21:11.120 --> 21:14.210
who might lose her baby,
so just let her be.

21:14.210 --> 21:16.460
♪♪

21:16.460 --> 21:18.540
Why?

21:18.540 --> 21:21.040
Why is she going to
lose this baby?

21:21.040 --> 21:21.920
[ Elevator bell dings ]

21:24.000 --> 21:26.330
I'm here.
My embolization
didn't work.

21:26.330 --> 21:27.500
The baby is in
severe distress.

21:27.500 --> 21:29.120
We have to save
the mother.

21:29.120 --> 21:30.830
I'm gonna go up now,
and I may need your help

21:30.830 --> 21:32.380
to do an emergency
hysterectomy.

21:32.380 --> 21:34.460
Does she know?
I just got
the husband here,

21:34.460 --> 21:36.170
and I'm gonna tell
them both now.

21:36.170 --> 21:37.960
I can help.
Great. Thank you.

21:39.210 --> 21:40.620
Douglas: But the baby
can't survive yet.

21:40.620 --> 21:43.620
Vincenzo: I can keep it safe
and sound outside the mother,

21:43.620 --> 21:47.000
but inside a simulated womb,
where it can develop,

21:47.000 --> 21:48.790
while your wife gets
the care and surgery

21:48.790 --> 21:50.120
she needs to survive.

21:50.120 --> 21:52.000
Teddy: What's going on?
Papa.

21:52.000 --> 21:54.330
Lizzie:
You can save the baby?

21:54.330 --> 21:55.830
You can save us both?

21:55.830 --> 21:58.080
Yes, I can.

21:58.080 --> 21:59.710
♪♪

22:05.120 --> 22:06.830
[ Elevator bell dings ]

22:06.830 --> 22:08.540
[ Indistinct conversations ]

22:08.540 --> 22:09.960
Morning!

22:09.960 --> 22:12.000
Sleep well?
Yeah.

22:12.000 --> 22:14.460
Yeah, it was
a good idea to...

22:14.460 --> 22:18.880
Sleep is so important
for the, um...

22:18.880 --> 22:20.330
Brain?
Sure.

22:20.330 --> 22:22.790
When -- What --
What are you doing today?

22:22.790 --> 22:24.880
Uh, I was gonna check out
Logan's Nerve Block talk.

22:24.880 --> 22:26.500
Oh, me too.
Perfect.

22:26.500 --> 22:29.080
Yeah, but when
is your thing?

22:29.080 --> 22:30.790
Uh, you d-- you don't
want to go to that.

22:30.790 --> 22:32.500
Of course I do!

22:32.500 --> 22:34.460
But first, coffee.

22:36.330 --> 22:38.920
Which is not in my room.

22:38.920 --> 22:41.250
There's coffee in my room.

22:41.250 --> 22:42.960
Nope!

22:42.960 --> 22:46.330
[ Indistinct conversations ]

22:46.330 --> 22:49.000
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Nasraban, 4521.

22:49.000 --> 22:50.960
Dr. Ethan Nasraban, 4521.

22:50.960 --> 22:53.540
[ Clears throat ]
Grey, you're being creepy.

22:53.540 --> 22:54.750
I'm creepy?

22:54.750 --> 22:56.540
They're calling you
the ruler of Atlantis.

22:56.540 --> 22:58.790
Yeah, well, I mean,
it's pretty cool.

22:58.790 --> 23:00.420
Tilapia skin's
rich in collagen,

23:00.420 --> 23:02.040
which promotes healing.

23:02.040 --> 23:04.380
No more need for painful
dressing changes.

23:04.380 --> 23:05.750
I'm looking to apply
a lot of those properties

23:05.750 --> 23:06.830
to my spray-on skin.

23:06.830 --> 23:09.120
Ooh, the spray-on skin
is back?

23:09.120 --> 23:11.710
Well, your boyfriend is putting
lambs in zip-lock bags.

23:11.710 --> 23:13.620
He can't be the only one
changing the world, you know?

23:13.620 --> 23:15.250
He's not my boyfriend.

23:15.250 --> 23:16.580
Well, that's not
what Maggie said.

23:16.580 --> 23:18.920
Or Richard.

23:18.920 --> 23:22.210
Anyway, I'm not sure how
that project is going.

23:22.210 --> 23:23.880
I have a bad feeling.

23:23.880 --> 23:25.750
Why? Why is that?

23:25.750 --> 23:27.540
Never mind.
I'm just gonna be supportive.

23:27.540 --> 23:29.670
Ah. I get it.

23:29.670 --> 23:31.830
Because he's
your boyfriend.

23:31.830 --> 23:34.080
How is Maggie doing? Is she
nervous about the TV thing?

23:34.080 --> 23:36.000
Well, she put
her makeup on twice,

23:36.000 --> 23:38.170
and then they wiped it right off
and then re-applied it, so...

23:38.170 --> 23:40.380
-[ Laughs ]
-It's going great.

23:40.380 --> 23:41.960
Hey, can he breathe
underwater?

23:41.960 --> 23:44.080
Just keep walking, Grey.
[ Laughs ]

23:44.080 --> 23:46.460
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

23:46.460 --> 23:48.250
She told you
she's afraid to go home?

23:48.250 --> 23:50.500
But she seems
to be doing fine.
And she is.

23:50.500 --> 23:52.040
But, you know,
mental illness

23:52.040 --> 23:55.250
is like cancer and diabetes,
any other chronic illness --

23:55.250 --> 23:56.620
you have to monitor.

23:56.620 --> 23:58.040
Why was she even
telling you this?

23:58.040 --> 24:00.380
I asked her how she was.

24:00.380 --> 24:02.960
Is this some kind of
crusade for you, Bailey?
W--

24:02.960 --> 24:05.540
I mean, first going after
Dr. DeLuca, now my mom?

24:05.540 --> 24:07.710
Wh-- I'm not "going after"
anyone.

24:07.710 --> 24:09.000
'Cause it seems like
you're prejudiced.

24:09.000 --> 24:10.120
It -- What?

24:10.120 --> 24:11.920
Against people
with mental illness.

24:13.120 --> 24:15.170
I'm not prejudiced,
you jackass!

24:15.170 --> 24:16.710
I am a person
with mental illness!

24:16.710 --> 24:18.710
[ Sighs ]

24:18.710 --> 24:21.040
And I cope with it
every day.

24:21.040 --> 24:22.710
I take my medication,
and I'm doing great.

24:22.710 --> 24:24.710
But, sometimes,
I need help.

24:24.710 --> 24:27.460
That's -- That's why I asked
you to stay on as chief.

24:27.460 --> 24:30.330
And it's hard to ask
for that help.

24:30.330 --> 24:33.170
Your mother needs to ask,
and she can't.

24:33.170 --> 24:35.920
Your job is to make it
so that she can.

24:35.920 --> 24:38.170
So do your job, son.

24:38.170 --> 24:39.830
Prejudiced.
[ Scoffs ]

24:39.830 --> 24:42.080
Jackass.

24:42.080 --> 24:43.620
[ Door creaks ]

24:43.620 --> 24:45.040
[ Cellphone chimes, vibrates ]

24:46.670 --> 24:48.120
What the hell?

24:50.000 --> 24:51.500
Tell me what happened.

24:51.500 --> 24:53.460
Last night,
I found Vincenzo DeLuca

24:53.460 --> 24:56.710
counseling my patient to gestate
her premature baby in a bag.
[ Sighs ]

24:56.710 --> 24:58.580
What?
He talked to your patient?

24:58.580 --> 25:00.170
Yeah. He said that
the fetus would be

25:00.170 --> 25:03.080
safe and sound
in an artificial womb.

25:03.080 --> 25:05.580
[ Sighs ] Listen.
He -- He's working on --

25:05.580 --> 25:07.000
I transfused multiple times
overnight to buy time,

25:07.000 --> 25:08.210
but I'm just wasting blood.

25:08.210 --> 25:09.540
I'm gonna
have to operate soon.

25:09.540 --> 25:12.580
But, Alex, we can do this?

25:12.580 --> 25:15.670
I mean, we can save
my patient's 21-week-old baby?

25:15.670 --> 25:18.000
Can we really
save them both?

25:20.080 --> 25:23.170
Hey.
Have you seen Maggie?

25:23.170 --> 25:24.460
Maggie: Um, I know.
[ Gasps ]

25:24.460 --> 25:26.380
Is that the woman from
"Good Morning Seattle"?

25:26.380 --> 25:28.880
Huh!
Yeah, Maggie's
very fancy now.
Shh.

25:28.880 --> 25:32.330
Right, uh-huh. I-I -- I took
the job here before anyone knew.

25:32.330 --> 25:34.120
And you found a family.

25:34.120 --> 25:35.960
Yeah. I mean, I-I knew that,
uh, my mom

25:35.960 --> 25:38.330
had been here
and she was gone.

25:38.330 --> 25:41.000
But I had no idea
that I had a sister.

25:41.000 --> 25:45.880
And, um, a man who, um...

25:45.880 --> 25:49.380
I have a father [chuckles] --
Bill Pierce, who raised me.

25:49.380 --> 25:50.960
Hi, Dad. [ Chuckles ]

25:50.960 --> 25:55.120
Um, but Richard Webber
is, uh, a bonus.

25:55.120 --> 25:56.500
I don't know how else
to describe it.

25:56.500 --> 25:58.000
I'm -- I'm...

25:58.000 --> 25:59.250
I'm very lucky.

25:59.250 --> 26:01.540
Sounds like
a pleasant surprise.

26:01.540 --> 26:03.540
It's more than pleasant.

26:03.540 --> 26:05.040
It's life-changing.

26:05.040 --> 26:07.080
Oh, my God.
But you missed that
crucial window,

26:07.080 --> 26:08.750
the chance to meet
your mother.
Jackson: What?

26:08.750 --> 26:10.620
I did, but...
That's a sign.

26:10.620 --> 26:12.170
I came here to ask her
whether I should

26:12.170 --> 26:14.380
find my birth mother,
and then she's --

26:14.380 --> 26:16.080
That is a sign.
...gain a perspective
on her

26:16.080 --> 26:17.920
that no one else got.
What?

26:17.920 --> 26:19.210
Jackson: Uh, nothing.

26:19.210 --> 26:20.540
-Um.
-Do you think...

26:20.540 --> 26:22.790
What?

26:22.790 --> 26:25.120
I connected with
my father a while back,

26:25.120 --> 26:26.460
and it was not
the best idea.

26:26.460 --> 26:28.250
It didn't alleviate
any of my pain.

26:28.250 --> 26:30.120
It just kind of
created more.

26:30.120 --> 26:32.250
So unless there's some big
answer that you're looking for,

26:32.250 --> 26:34.670
you might just want
to let it go.

26:34.670 --> 26:36.170
Maggie: My point was,
I was -- I was raised by...

26:36.170 --> 26:37.460
You took my sign down.

26:37.460 --> 26:39.540
...wonderful parents
who encouraged me

26:39.540 --> 26:41.330
to go for everything
I wanted.

26:41.330 --> 26:43.540
Woman: When we come back,
we're making wraps --

26:43.540 --> 26:46.710
the sandwich solution that
brightens your kid's lunch box.

26:46.710 --> 26:48.380
No, no, no.

26:48.380 --> 26:50.670
Papa, why were you
even in there?

26:50.670 --> 26:54.380
Papa.
[ Speaking Italian ]

26:54.380 --> 26:57.830
[ Speaking Italian ]

26:57.830 --> 27:00.420
[ Speaking Italian ]
Dr. DeLuca,
you can't promise

27:00.420 --> 27:02.330
fake procedures
with my patients.

27:02.330 --> 27:03.500
Please.

27:03.500 --> 27:06.000
Tell me something you try
that could work.

27:06.000 --> 27:07.960
I have a living subject.

27:07.960 --> 27:10.580
And a dead one --
just last night!

27:10.580 --> 27:13.580
P-Papa, you are reckless!
You are thoughtless!

27:13.580 --> 27:15.290
You just -- You just --
All right, right now,
we have a mess

27:15.290 --> 27:16.330
to clean up
with this patient.

27:16.330 --> 27:17.710
And you're gonna help.

27:19.420 --> 27:21.380
No, no, no, no.
You stay here.

27:21.380 --> 27:22.750
I mean it.

27:22.750 --> 27:24.170
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:24.170 --> 27:25.540
You've done enough.

27:25.540 --> 27:27.580
♪♪

27:27.580 --> 27:29.880
[ Sighs ]

27:29.880 --> 27:31.790
[ Glass shatters ]

27:31.790 --> 27:33.120
♪♪

27:33.120 --> 27:35.330
[ Monitor beeping ]

27:35.330 --> 27:37.000
I have to take you
up to surgery now,

27:37.000 --> 27:40.330
and I will most likely
have to do a hysterectomy.

27:42.750 --> 27:45.170
Wait. N-No.

27:45.170 --> 27:48.880
That doctor -- he said
he could save the baby.

27:48.880 --> 27:51.080
The procedure he told you about
is not yet available.

27:51.080 --> 27:52.330
But he said it was.

27:52.330 --> 27:53.830
He said he could do it.

27:53.830 --> 27:56.290
Teddy: It -- It hasn't been
tested in people.

27:56.290 --> 27:58.210
We don't have approval to try
this procedure on your baby.

27:58.210 --> 27:59.710
I-I approve.

28:01.960 --> 28:05.460
I'm the mother.
I give you approval.

28:07.460 --> 28:09.330
Do it.

28:09.330 --> 28:10.460
Try it!

28:13.250 --> 28:14.620
I-I can't.

28:14.620 --> 28:19.830
[ Voice breaking ]
You'll just...let our baby die?

28:19.830 --> 28:21.210
I'm sorry.

28:23.380 --> 28:25.000
[ Crying ]

28:25.000 --> 28:27.460
[ Beeping continues ]

28:27.460 --> 28:30.000
Um, is there any chance,
any chance at all?

28:31.790 --> 28:33.170
[ Sniffles ]

28:33.170 --> 28:34.540
Carina:
I'll deliver your baby

28:34.540 --> 28:36.920
and make sure
the baby is comfortable

28:36.920 --> 28:40.000
for as long as I can.

28:40.000 --> 28:43.790
And -- And, uh,
you can...hold her.

28:43.790 --> 28:46.670
[ Sighs ]

28:46.670 --> 28:49.080
[ Sobbing ]

28:54.330 --> 28:56.330
Link: This is Jason.

28:56.330 --> 28:58.210
In 2014, Jason
was a junior and goalie

28:58.210 --> 28:59.380
in high school and club soccer.

28:59.380 --> 29:00.920
Scholarship material.

29:02.420 --> 29:04.880
Protecting the goal got
him a patellar fracture,

29:04.880 --> 29:07.960
comminuted tibial plateau,
torn meniscus, ACL.

29:07.960 --> 29:10.460
Still, he got the team
to the state finals.

29:10.460 --> 29:12.710
[ Laughter ]
He required multiple surgeries,

29:12.710 --> 29:15.790
all of which went well,
had intense P.T. sessions,

29:15.790 --> 29:18.790
and I prescribed him
opioids for the pain.

29:22.960 --> 29:25.170
When Jason died
two years later

29:25.170 --> 29:26.670
in a car accident
under the influence,

29:26.670 --> 29:30.210
I realized that
he was a drug addict.

29:30.210 --> 29:33.790
And I had been his first dealer.
[ Crowd murmuring ]

29:33.790 --> 29:35.960
[ Clears throat ]
But here's my real point.

29:35.960 --> 29:38.170
If I had to do it
all over again,

29:38.170 --> 29:40.080
I would've made
the same decision.

29:40.080 --> 29:41.960
[ Murmuring continues ]

29:41.960 --> 29:43.580
Ah -- Let me tell you why.

29:43.580 --> 29:47.250
♪♪

29:47.250 --> 29:51.120
Opioids are undeniably
a very effective way

29:51.120 --> 29:53.120
of fooling the body into
thinking everything is okay.

29:53.120 --> 29:54.170
♪♪

29:54.170 --> 29:55.960
[ Monitor beeping ]

29:55.960 --> 30:03.080
♪♪

30:03.080 --> 30:06.000
♪♪

30:06.000 --> 30:07.960
Are you
going to intubate?

30:07.960 --> 30:09.330
No.

30:09.330 --> 30:10.670
That would just be cruel.

30:10.670 --> 30:11.880
Teddy: Heaney clamp.

30:11.880 --> 30:12.670
-Pull back.
-Mm-hmm.

30:12.670 --> 30:13.920
Get that.

30:13.920 --> 30:15.120
Yeah. Here?

30:15.120 --> 30:16.380
Yep.

30:16.380 --> 30:18.960
♪♪

30:18.960 --> 30:19.960
Okay.
I got it.

30:19.960 --> 30:21.120
Okay.

30:21.120 --> 30:23.120
0-vicryl pop-off.

30:23.120 --> 30:26.620
♪♪

30:26.620 --> 30:28.710
[ Door creaks ]

30:28.710 --> 30:30.420
[ Indistinct conversations ]

30:30.420 --> 30:32.500
What did you think
you were doing?

30:32.500 --> 30:33.790
You know --
[ Scoffs ]

30:33.790 --> 30:35.000
I mean,
you must know --

30:35.000 --> 30:36.960
that you couldn't
try it on their baby.

30:36.960 --> 30:40.170
Why would you give them
false hope like that?

30:40.170 --> 30:42.920
We have the tools
right there.

30:42.920 --> 30:44.880
I could've saved
a person's life --

30:44.880 --> 30:47.170
Not yet!
It's not ready.

30:47.170 --> 30:48.830
We don't know if
the baby would survive,

30:48.830 --> 30:51.080
how the baby would survive,
if -- if the brain

30:51.080 --> 30:53.330
would have deficits --
Oh, porca miseria, stop.

30:53.330 --> 30:54.790
Stop.

30:54.790 --> 30:57.120
You sound just like
the rest of them.

30:59.710 --> 31:02.120
Oh, my God.

31:02.120 --> 31:04.420
This is it.

31:04.420 --> 31:06.830
This is just like
it was that night.

31:06.830 --> 31:08.080
What night?

31:09.250 --> 31:10.920
Andrea, what night?

31:10.920 --> 31:12.000
What do you mean
"what night"?

31:12.000 --> 31:14.080
The night
four people died, Papa!

31:14.080 --> 31:17.210
It is
just like that night.

31:17.210 --> 31:19.380
Seven people
come in mangled.

31:19.380 --> 31:21.170
I am the only one there.
No, no, no, no.

31:21.170 --> 31:22.540
People came,
people offered to help,

31:22.540 --> 31:23.790
and you wouldn't let them.

31:23.790 --> 31:25.500
I was doing the job
that needed to be done!

31:25.500 --> 31:27.540
♪ And the roads are filling up ♪
You see, this is exactly
what they talk about.

31:27.540 --> 31:29.210
This is delusional, Papa.

31:29.210 --> 31:31.380
Am I supposed to stop,

31:31.380 --> 31:34.960
let another doctor try
and continue where I am?
♪ Everybody's going somewhere ♪

31:34.960 --> 31:36.420
They would've died!
They did!

31:36.420 --> 31:38.830
They did die!
♪ But, baby, I know ♪

31:38.830 --> 31:41.290
And tonight,
a pregnant mother

31:41.290 --> 31:43.250
might lose her unborn baby
to a car accident,

31:43.250 --> 31:46.620
which is tragic,
but it's merciful

31:46.620 --> 31:48.540
compared to watching
it die in a bag...
♪ I was standing
on the ceiling ♪

31:48.540 --> 31:49.750
...at the hands
of some scientist

31:49.750 --> 31:51.500
who doesn't know
what the hell he's doing!

31:51.500 --> 31:52.790
♪♪

31:52.790 --> 31:55.080
Papa, please tell me
you can see that.

31:55.080 --> 31:56.620
♪ Saw a plane crash
on the news ♪

31:56.620 --> 31:58.580
[ Voice breaking ]
Are you too sick to see that?

31:58.580 --> 32:00.710
♪♪

32:00.710 --> 32:02.880
♪ They say the chances
of that happening ♪

32:02.880 --> 32:04.250
How is the baby?

32:04.250 --> 32:05.460
♪♪

32:05.460 --> 32:09.920
♪ Are about the same
as finding you ♪

32:09.920 --> 32:12.290
Carina:
Would you like to...

32:12.290 --> 32:13.670
♪♪

32:13.670 --> 32:14.960
Yeah.

32:14.960 --> 32:18.790
♪ What I need ♪

32:18.790 --> 32:20.750
♪♪

32:20.750 --> 32:25.580
♪ What I need ♪

32:25.580 --> 32:27.880
♪♪

32:27.880 --> 32:33.170
♪ What I need ♪

32:33.170 --> 32:35.540
♪♪

32:35.540 --> 32:37.330
Hi.
♪ Is you ♪

32:37.330 --> 32:38.920
[ Breathes sharply ]

32:38.920 --> 32:40.710
♪ And me ♪

32:40.710 --> 32:43.000
♪♪

32:43.000 --> 32:44.670
[ Crying quietly ]

32:44.670 --> 32:49.750
♪♪

32:49.750 --> 32:54.500
♪♪

32:54.500 --> 32:56.920
♪♪

32:56.920 --> 32:58.880
Lizzie: [ Crying ]

32:58.880 --> 33:03.670
♪ What I need ♪

33:03.670 --> 33:05.670
[ Sighs ]

33:05.670 --> 33:10.540
♪ What I need ♪
[ Sobbing ]

33:10.540 --> 33:13.250
♪♪

33:13.250 --> 33:15.290
♪ What I need ♪

33:15.290 --> 33:18.750
Teddy. You okay?
Mm-hmm.

33:18.750 --> 33:20.460
♪ Is you ♪

33:20.460 --> 33:22.210
♪♪

33:22.210 --> 33:23.620
♪ And me ♪

33:23.620 --> 33:24.670
♪♪

33:24.670 --> 33:26.380
[ Crying ]

33:26.380 --> 33:30.000
♪ I'm paralyzed ♪

33:30.000 --> 33:34.580
♪ Like there's half of me ♪

33:34.580 --> 33:37.120
♪ That's missing ♪

33:37.120 --> 33:40.830
[ Crying continues ]

33:40.830 --> 33:45.960
♪♪

33:45.960 --> 33:48.830
♪ What I need ♪

33:48.830 --> 33:51.620
[ Crying, sniffling ]

33:51.620 --> 33:53.210
♪ Is you ♪

33:53.210 --> 33:55.080
[ Crying continues ]
♪ And me ♪

34:00.750 --> 34:03.040
Look, I believe
in your research. I do.

34:03.040 --> 34:04.080
But what happened
with this patient

34:04.080 --> 34:05.170
was a major breach
of protocol.

34:05.170 --> 34:06.540
I can't have that.
So I've decided --

34:06.540 --> 34:09.040
You need to reconsider right now
what you're about to say.

34:09.040 --> 34:11.500
DeLuca:
Papa, don't argue.
Do not interrupt me.

34:11.500 --> 34:13.750
Papa, you need to get help
before somebody gets hurt.

34:13.750 --> 34:15.000
Like that baby?

34:17.000 --> 34:19.880
I might have saved
that baby.

34:19.880 --> 34:23.710
But you let it die,
and you let it die,

34:23.710 --> 34:26.420
and you let it die!

34:26.420 --> 34:29.960
Because of your cowardice
and laziness,

34:29.960 --> 34:34.420
you will never know if that
child had to die at your hands.

34:34.420 --> 34:36.250
Damn it!

34:36.250 --> 34:38.210
You're stopping
my research?

34:38.210 --> 34:40.170
That what
you're about to say?

34:40.170 --> 34:42.880
No! You don't get
my research!

34:42.880 --> 34:44.000
You don't deserve it!

34:44.000 --> 34:45.460
I take it and go!

34:45.460 --> 34:46.830
Cretini!

34:46.830 --> 34:50.920
♪♪

34:50.920 --> 34:53.290
[ Sighs softly ]

34:53.290 --> 34:54.750
♪♪

34:54.750 --> 34:56.500
[ Indistinct conversations ]

34:59.040 --> 35:01.460
[ Oil boiling ]

35:01.460 --> 35:04.170
[ Indistinct conversations ]

35:04.170 --> 35:05.920
[ Horns honking in distance ]

35:05.920 --> 35:07.880
Mmm. This actually
makes it worth it.

35:07.880 --> 35:09.960
Mmm.

35:09.960 --> 35:11.170
I thought I read
the text wrong,

35:11.170 --> 35:12.380
but, no, you are hosting
a "fish fry."

35:12.380 --> 35:13.580
Yeah, waste not,
want not.

35:13.580 --> 35:15.500
Hey, grab a plate.

35:15.500 --> 35:18.170
Bailey,
can you do me a favor?

35:18.170 --> 35:19.620
Look,
I need your help now.

35:19.620 --> 35:23.250
[ Sighs ] Can you take back the
chiefship, just for two days?

35:23.250 --> 35:24.830
[ Sighs ]
I still have
a couple weeks left.

35:24.830 --> 35:26.710
I'm gonna take them.
I-It's not
a fast-food joint, Karev.

35:26.710 --> 35:28.620
We don't cover shifts
for each other.

35:28.620 --> 35:30.460
I need to fly with my mom
back to Iowa.

35:30.460 --> 35:32.210
I talked to her,
and you were right.

35:32.210 --> 35:34.330
She needs to get home.
Did you tell her
I talked to you?

35:34.330 --> 35:36.250
Hell, no. I look like
a thoughtful son.

35:36.250 --> 35:37.120
Hm.

35:39.290 --> 35:42.330
I will try to fill
your shoes.

35:42.330 --> 35:45.040
Hey, tell your mother
thank you for the hat.

35:45.040 --> 35:46.540
[ Laughter ]

35:46.540 --> 35:47.420
[ Chuckles ]

35:48.830 --> 35:50.250
[ Knock on door ]

35:58.790 --> 36:00.380
[ Door creaks ]

36:00.380 --> 36:01.670
You missed the good part.

36:01.670 --> 36:03.250
There was a good part?

36:03.250 --> 36:05.500
You know, "error of my ways,"
all that stuff.

36:05.500 --> 36:07.210
I will see you in Seattle.

36:07.210 --> 36:08.960
[ Door creaks ]

36:08.960 --> 36:11.120
You know, I-I didn't
really have a choice

36:11.120 --> 36:12.500
but to give him
those drugs.

36:12.500 --> 36:14.120
You would've done
the exact same thing I did.

36:15.620 --> 36:17.880
I absolutely
would not have,

36:17.880 --> 36:19.460
because I understand
how addiction works.

36:19.460 --> 36:21.670
Back then, you would've.
And I believe
the drug companies

36:21.670 --> 36:23.120
also understand it,

36:23.120 --> 36:25.210
and they have made billions
on the back of it.

36:25.210 --> 36:27.960
Jason's leg was caught between
a defender and a goalpost.

36:27.960 --> 36:30.670
His knee was bent
90 degrees sideways.

36:30.670 --> 36:33.670
No amount of ibuprofen or sound
baths were gonna help him.

36:33.670 --> 36:36.750
He was talking
about suicide.
Yeah, and you
gave him the means!

36:36.750 --> 36:38.040
And you would do it again.
You said you --

36:38.040 --> 36:39.750
Not the same way,
not blindly.

36:42.290 --> 36:43.750
[ Door creaks ]

36:43.750 --> 36:45.170
[ Door clicks shut ]

36:45.170 --> 36:49.210
Amelia, science
has given us a way

36:49.210 --> 36:52.380
to tell the brain
to stop unbearable pain.

36:52.380 --> 36:54.880
So far, there's no alternative
as effect--
Are you just giving me
your lecture now?

36:54.880 --> 36:56.290
A child is dead!

36:56.290 --> 36:57.750
You failed him!

36:59.580 --> 37:00.580
And you think
I haven't felt that

37:00.580 --> 37:04.000
every day
since Jason's funeral?

37:04.000 --> 37:07.790
When I saw the look on his
mother's face, I left medicine.

37:09.080 --> 37:11.620
For a year, I only trusted
myself to fix bikes.

37:11.620 --> 37:12.830
I quit.

37:12.830 --> 37:14.580
But, then, I got mad.

37:14.580 --> 37:17.170
Because, yeah, I failed,
the same way we've all failed.

37:17.170 --> 37:19.210
We blew the first rule --
do no harm.

37:20.580 --> 37:23.250
But he needed those drugs
immediately post-op,

37:23.250 --> 37:24.330
and that's where
it should've stopped.

37:24.330 --> 37:26.250
I should've warned him
and his mother

37:26.250 --> 37:27.830
about the dangers
of dependency.

37:27.830 --> 37:29.500
I-I should've followed up
with his GP.

37:29.500 --> 37:30.920
The system is broken,

37:30.920 --> 37:33.500
and I'm doing everything I can
to try to fix it.

37:37.080 --> 37:39.120
So you're saying
I missed the good part.

